The Civil Rights Movement has issued a travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Benefit of Colored People (NAACP) has issued a warning to colored people traveling to Missouri based on discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
“The NAACP’s State of Missouri Travel Recommendation, effective August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors and residents of Missouri to pay increased attention when traveling across the state as a result of a series of controversial racially motivated incidents to which they are currently associated.”
The NAACP said it has taken this step on the basis of current Missouri state laws that make it difficult to defend racist-motivated acts in court, as well as due to the actions of law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities.
“There is a violation of civil rights.
People are stopped by police officers just because of the color of their skin, they are attacked or killed," Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri State Police, told the Kansas City Star.
"We have the largest number of complaints yet."
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization to the U.S. state.
Among the incidents cited by the organization were racially motivated attacks directed at black skin students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in controversial circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while traveling across the state and was thrown in jail without charge for the crime.
The travel recommendation also points to a recent statement by the Missouri State Supreme Court, which states that black-skinned drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped by the police.
“The purpose of the travel advisory is to alert people and warn their families, friends and co-workers of what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared - they should take the money with them for a possible bail or warn their relatives that they are going to travel the state."
According to current figures from the FBI’s Hate Crime Reporting Program, there were hundreds of hate behavior cases in Missouri in 2015, making it the 16th state among all states.
The travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri law, which makes it easier to sue the company for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states passed an immigration law that allows state officials to detain people on the basis of a violation of this law, which according to the ACLU is supposed to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the U.S. Department of State for foreign countries, but recently, advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the U.S.
