Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she does not use a stove.
In fact, it rarely uses a pan.
In her wooden hut, located in the capital city of Paniai Enarotali in the Indonesian province of Papua, a woman usually simply throws sweet potatoes - in the language of local "notes" - directly into the fire.
After half an hour, remove the potato and taste it with unwashed hands.
Bardina sits on muddy ground - the house is not equipped with furniture - where she also does her daily work, such as washing laundry in muddy water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in a room without a roof flushes the toilet.
As the youngest of her husband’s four wives, she was not assigned any field to cultivate.
Polygamy is common here.
Working until late at night poses a danger: most of the men from the village are unemployed and often drink alcohol. In addition, the village is inhabited by soldiers.
"In the afternoon after five o'clock, no one will be allowed to wander around the village," says Bardina.
It is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 seniors were forced to vote in the form of a public raising of hands before the occupying army.
The current anti-Dutch protest movement quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region with the exception of foreign journalists or civil rights monitors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a remote and desolate city, where you can get to after a ninety-minute flight from the capital of Jayapura province to Nabira, and then a five-hour stomach-shutting drive.
There is no public transport in this place.
The city with 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs made of woolen sheets in shades of gray and rusty color.
Very few Indonesians, journalists, and practically no foreigners, looked at this place.
Before the arrival of Christians, the local people worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
"We weren't used to wearing these dresses," says Bardina, pointing to his colorful, hand-knitted turban, dark T-shirt and bright skirt.
"We used to only wear leaves."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province - 28% of the population lives below the poverty line and the country's child mortality and literacy rate is one of the worst in all of Asia.
At the same time, it is an Indonesian country of gold.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoeenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai – a rocky province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports the extraction of wood worth an estimated $78 billion.
These riches, however, are a source of suffering for Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, Freeport paid about $20 million to local military officials and units between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 for one officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore hard-pressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969 and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian army.
Mass killings in Papua during the 1970s were tantamount to genocide, according to the Asian Human Rights Commission.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that took place last year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture – according to another report, rape and electrocution is particularly popular – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrators.
“It’s difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The whole situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan resources attract colonists to Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million people, 83% report Christianity, but the demographics are changing with an influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
Local people are fighting for survival.
“Immigrants started selling chickens and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old who was born in Paniai and moved to Jayapura for work.
"The original inhabitants of Papua - mama-mama (women) - so they lost their job."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised to address inequality and human rights abuses in his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured his way to the presidential palace in the Jakarta 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our heart was broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi with the hope that he will hear our call for justice,” You said.
The fact is that only two months after the October inauguration of Jakovi, Paniai experienced a great shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children sang a Christmas song at a campfire in the town of Enarotali, when two Indonesian soldiers emerged from the darkness of the night on motorcycles.
Two of the surprised children told them to turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by this exclamation and tone, which was uttered and later returned with four other soldiers, said local priest Yavedt Tebai.
Two of the soldiers in a drunken state chased a group of children and beat them with their weapons, reported the victims and witnesses of the events.
One of the soldiers then set fire to a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby electoral commission building and things were still going up the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and army headquarters, demanding justice.
They came up with ceremonial hunting bows and performed a waita dance – in which a circle is run and a bird song is imitated – of the Papuan tribe of Mee Pago.
Several Protestants began to throw stones at the buildings.
With increasing tension, the soldiers were given an order over the radio: “If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot,” according to TIME magazine in an official document, the content of which has never been published in the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of Enarotali Kego Koto district, recognized the danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one heeded his words.
"When I turned, someone shot me in the left wrist," he told TIME on the veranda of his painted wooden house.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but according to him, the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shots were fired," he added.
According to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, one of the locals, Alfius Youw, was hit three times.
"I ran to the body to make sure it was really him," Yohanes told TIME in a sullen voice, which, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
The Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were merely “ensuring” the station that was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," a Papuan police spokesman, Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many others were injured.
The report of the murders was leaked to the Jakarta media the following day.
Three weeks later, he gave Jokowi a passionate speech in Jayapur, expressing his understanding for the families of the victims and promising to deal with the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem, so that it can never happen again," he said.
In October 2016, the Minister of National Security, Wiranto, announced that he would introduce an out-of-court mechanism to resolve violent acts that had occurred in the past.
Almost immediately, however, excuses began to be uttered.
“Most of the violent acts have happened a long time ago.
Some of them happened in the 90s of the last century and some at the beginning of the 21st century.
I mean, we are determined to punish these violent acts, but it will not be an easy task," he said.
In a June 5 interview with TIME, which was held in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he does not plan to introduce any measures in Papua.
Instead, say that “all cases will be brought before the court.”
Wiranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” on the basis of more than 1,000 deaths during the 1999 independent elections in East Timor, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua, including the incident in Paniai, had so far been settled.
The families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai welcomed his claim with distrust.
“I’ve been asked a total of four times in the last three years, but so far I haven’t expected anything,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
As he says, a few years later, he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid," he said.
"I'm afraid the army will arrest me or someone will shoot me."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many residents of Paniai, who are afraid to talk about the incident.
According to him, he was killed by members of the army after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army started looking for me," he said.
And the shooting hasn't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired at villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
The fight, in which one person died and another 17 were injured, took place between villagers and a construction company manager, who refused to provide assistance in transporting a man unconscious to the hospital.
Ravianus Dow, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company building.
According to the police, the villagers threw stones at the belongings and their answers were a warning shot.
However, locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) started shooting into the crowd and killed one person.
"There was a panic, we were afraid of retribution," 29-year-old Domingo Badia, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the injured, told TIME.
"I didn't leave the house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament demanded the punishment of the police officers involved and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the side of the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of indigenous peoples of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes, who live in the central highlands.
Many of them have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of insurgents that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and abducting Indonesian police.
Some of the OPM leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks, the army has in recent years arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of Paniai residents, all under the pretext of “ensuring national sovereignty”.
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known among the inhabitants of Papua as a "tragic and forgotten place".
Oil is poured into the fire by poverty.
