Pruitt, who had long held the position of Oklahoma Attorney General before taking on the role of EPA chief Donald Trump, has long served as a staunch opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industries.
The sudden turnaround on Wednesday is the biggest legal failure for Pruitt’s regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that an EPA contractor had overstepped its authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration’s plan to require oil and gas companies to reduce methane emissions.
In a statement issued Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed its version of the ozone standards and strengthened the EPA’s commitment to cooperate with states through complex processes and meeting new standards within a given time frame.
“The EPA’s previous administration often failed to meet deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set plans,” said Pruitt, who has filed more than a dozen lawsuits with the EPA in his previous position.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation and we take the deadline seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it.”
The EPA said in a statement that Pruitt could at some point use "the possibility of delay and all other legally available authorities" to ensure that regulations "will be based on sound policies and the most accessible information."
