There is a shortage of tourists in China.
Beijing is losing billions because of its visa policy.
For decades, China has been trying to exert its influence without the use of force.
It spends $10 billion annually to support language schools and the construction of universities abroad, pushes its entertainment industry to foreign markets, and seeks to attract Western tourists.
Beijing is not going to do that.
The state media there are talking about a plan to turn tourism into a driving force for economic transformation and modernization.
Last year, however, the number of visitors increased by only 3.8 percent, and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, assesses the situation in the world's most populous country, Professor of Economics from Beijing University Christopher Balding in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for everything is the Chinese visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free access to China, and the citizens of the other countries have to pay their visas in advance.
Chinese officials in the US are therefore in crowds comparable to Chinese New Year celebrations.
The visa costs $140, but if you don’t want to wait long hours in the front line, you’ll have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study by the Journal of Economics and Finance showed that the need for a visa reduces the number of visitors to a given country by 70 percent.
In 2015, only two million Americans visited mainland China, while Hong Kong, which accounts for less than three percent of China’s gross domestic product and has less than one percent of its population, visited 1.8 million Americans.
China often deepens this problem itself when tourism uses it to realize its political goals, for example, in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China curtailed transportation to South Korea in the spring as part of a rift around the South Korean anti-missile system, the South Koreans retaliated and China avoided it.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw an increase of 85 percent.
All this has an impact on macroeconomic stability.
According to a recently published report by the US central bank, the Fed could leave China as much as $190 billion as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China, as part of the sale of the currency to incoming tourists, will receive about $35 billion a year.
According to official figures on the development of the balance of payments, China had a deficit of 217 billion dollars in tourism last year, which is equal to 44 percent of the total Chinese surplus in trade in goods.
A small number of tourists, therefore, strike a very painful blow to the country, which anxiously prevents the outflow of capital.
However, the above-mentioned factors are only one manifestation of a more general reluctance towards foreigners.
In many parts of China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, there were fewer than a million foreigners living in China.
There are also a number of cities in the United States.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroad of immigration, has twice as many.
A number of scientific papers show that immigrants tend to revitalise economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
You won’t find them in China.
Solving these problems will be politically challenging, but the step that is offered is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian countries, particularly India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and reduce visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.
