Moore's Ford Bridge Massacre: Activists Remember Racist lynching
The 1948 Ford Mercury drove past the nearby residents of Monroe, Georgia, and crept toward Moore's Ford Bridge.
However, before a car with four black-skinned passengers and a white driver could reach the bridge, a group of whites with guns blocked the road.
The group's leader - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - longed for a cigarette and looked at the car's windshield.
Inside, the passengers trembled with fear.
"We want that n---and Roger!" the man shouted.
"Bring it to me!"
The silence interrupts the cry of a young black man who is pulled from the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is only a reconstruction of the events that took place on July 22.
But when one of the men crosses the "Roger's" neck, the crowd exudes excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have been returning to Moore's Ford Bridge regularly to reconstruct the fateful night of 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Kukluxklan.
No one has been tried for murder yet.
“It’s amazing that not a single person has been arrested in all these years – even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identity,” said Tyrone Brooks, who helps re-organise the event.
"It's a stain on our history and a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and a lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event is a dramatic call to action. Every year the community of Monroe reminds that justice has not been done enough.
"We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all," Brooks said.
"Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot be started."
On July 27, 1946, a court physician covered up one of the bodies of the victims of lynching at Moore's Ford.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding districts were expected to take part in the lynching.
However, no one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite the fact that the suspects remain free for decades, supporters of civil rights claim that both the reasons for lynching - politics and sex - were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, by a decision of the Supreme Court, the black-skinned citizens of the state of Georgia were granted the right to participate for the first time in the elections scheduled for the summer.
And it was during the summer election period, according to the FBI, that black-skinned farmer Roger Malcolm had to stab the owner of Barnett Hester’s white-skinned land during a fight — allegedly because of his wife.
According to Brooks, Hester was said to have dated Malcolm's wife Dorothy and brought her into a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent landowner of the time, made a $600 bail for Malcolm.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and his cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
Upon their return from prison, just before the entrance to Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
"As it turns out, Harrison planned and organized the murders," the FBI said.
“It is also clear that there was a secret agreement between state and local law enforcement officials who not only participated in the lynching, but also got rid of the evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks made a brief statement on the whole matter.
"It was a massacre for the right to vote," he said.
“The murders had a clear subtext for all black-skinned locals: ‘This is how you’re going to get if you register and go to the polls.’”
The annual reconstruction of the Moore's Ford Bridge event is organized by Cassandra Greene for nearly a decade.
Her performance is pictorial, engaging and pretentious, showing deep-seated racism that many would like to see as extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction isn’t easy and it’s even harder to turn a blind eye, but Greene says it makes sense.
“No one wants to talk about lynching, because we have to deal with the unpleasant feelings that hide in each of us,” Greene said.
“But there can be no relationship between us if you don’t listen to what I’ve been through.”
The main rehearsals for this year's reconstruction began in June, and on the very first day, about 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - entered the room where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh serves as assistant director.
For many years, he played the leader of the Kukluxklan, but according to him, the role is exhausting.
"I feel bad about it because it contradicts who I am," Marbaugh said.
“I think it’s very important to remember this part of history regularly because we never want to go back to that time.”
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascon, who play Roger Malcolm, and Barnett Hester, are rehearsing their roles.
The show begins with a brawl - Malcolm quarrels with Hester and blames him for sleeping with his wife.
"Get out of my land n---e!"
Rascona can't do it.
There's a fight going on.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black-skinned actor) bursts into laughter.
Greene laughs the most.
"What happened?" asked Rascon.
He's confused.
Was I too rude?
"No," Greene said cheerfully.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'n-r' in that tone."
"Exactly," one of the black-skinned actors sneezes.
"You have to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; the hostility replaces the feeling of closeness.
Everyone wants the show to be authentic, just to make sure it's done for enough four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
Rascona this time emphasizes the correct pronunciation of the word on N.
No one laughs anymore.
The show ends violently and quickly.
Shout, gunshots... and the resulting silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings Billie Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
With every word, there is sadness in the room.
Against the background of all this, about a dozen spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
The population is almost the same number of blacks and whites.
One couple traveled all the way from New York to Ithaca, many watching them from the nearby area.
Each of them tolerates the local humid climate for nearly eight hours and Brooks leads them in the crowd to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Up until this point, the killings could have been viewed with distance, but now, standing in the same place where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is terrifying.
With the last words of the song, Greene invites the crowd to inspect the bodies.
The children kneel down at the victim's head, watch the fake blood and still bodies, and whisper something in their ear.
"They're not dead," the little boy said.
A few minutes later, Greene thanks the audience, and it's over.
The actors clean the rope and wipe away their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kukluxklan.
Nick Rascon embraces his two fellow actors and weeps in their arms; eventually he is overwhelmed by emotions.
"That's all right," one of the women whispered.
"We know you've got that role.
But you had a reason for that.”
Later that day, the audience will sit down with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple is excited to talk about a performance with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could hardly find words to express her feeling from today’s performance.
"It's hard to listen to those ugly words and look at the disgusting deeds... that people who look like you do because they look like you do," she said of the reconstruction.
“It makes me realize that lynching is still a topical topic,” she added, “it’s just called police fighting.”
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks sits in the courtroom, enjoying dinner and talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning the performance for the next year.
“Reconstructing these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we have had to go through – but it’s also a moment to think about,” he said.
“If we don’t learn from it, who knows... it could happen again.
People who do not know and study the history of their country are condemned to repeat it.”
