In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests, stating that in 442 cases it was found that “the person in question is 18 years of age or older”.
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the respondent stated that he would be 18 years old this year.
There were also criticisms of the medical method of determining age, which includes wisdom teeth X-rays and MRI scans of the knee joints, which are subsequently assessed by dentists and radiologists.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, who, among other things, deals with the assessment of the biological maturity of people to determine the age at which the person underwent puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of age-based measurements are right.
The assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we can’t determine the age accurately, we shouldn’t pretend otherwise,” he told Metro.
Forensic medical agency Agency's G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson defended the decision saying, "Generally speaking, the risk of misjudgment of a child as an adult is small.
