NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
From September, patients will have access to ‘transformational’ treatment for HIV prevention based on the decision of the Supreme Court on the financing of the NHS drug.
The National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial.
NSH agreed to fund the trial after the appeals court upheld last year’s Supreme Court ruling, saying the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, was taken by the NHS England from the mouth of Director General Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention,” while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment.”
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 will be fully implemented across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there are enough specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transsexual people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in the testing.
The program comes to taxpayers at <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and the NHS England signed a drug distribution contract this week after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully leverage the ever-expanding and increasingly successful effort to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than thirty years of efforts to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, Executive Director of the National AIDS Trust (NAT), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is given correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer the possibility of a change in the English HIV epidemic.
Since September, NSH will offer patients who are at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement.'
Ian Green, executive director of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “Priority number one must be the rapid deployment of testing across the country; we must ensure its availability to every patient.
“We now have a PrEP trial drug available, and we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.”
Shadow Health Secretary Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays on the part of the government.
The evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to a full understanding of the benefits of PrEP.
"It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV, and jointly end the spread of HIV in society."
