Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid their enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however terrifying.
Researchers have now revealed the conclusions of the first findings of an amazing creature about the size of a rhinoceros, whose perfectly preserved remains - which experts called 'Mona Lisa of dinosaurs' - were found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such an extent that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of his scaly skin and reported that the dinosaur had a 'problematic past'.
An article in the journal Current Biology stated that it is “the most well-preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best dinosaur species in the world.”
The fossil is a new species of the genus Nodosauridae. The dinosaur lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
His perfectly preserved condition was literally shocked by the researchers who described him as “really remarkable.”
According to National Geographic, the armored beetle is still the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
The find is by Shawn Funk, who discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011 while drilling in the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across something that looked like a foreign object and decided to explore it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to uncover an animal from a huge chunk of land weighing 1,100 kg.
After completing the work, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
“Just a little bit of blinking and you’ll believe you’re asleep,” said Caleb Brown, the head of the work, and a naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
“It will certainly be recorded in the history of history as one of the most beautiful and most preserved species of dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.”
By studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore — despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank — was highly likely to face a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a masking system that used many of today's animals.
Experts say that this allowed him to better merge with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The masking system suggests that he was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
Reports of the 110-million-year-old dinosaur Nodosauridae first appeared in the newspaper in May. It is currently available for viewing at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who spent more than 7,000 hours with the team carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shape of scales and armor throughout the body.
They discovered a method of masking that is commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the researchers’ findings are surprising because Borealopelta’s size far exceeds that of today’s animals using the same technique.
It is possible, therefore, that the dinosaur was such a number of predators that evolution gave the preference of masking over confrontation in survival.
Many modern-day masked animals — such as deer, zebras, or bandits — are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to fight for its surviving literal.
“The predation of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur vividly illustrates the dangers posed by predators during the Cretaceous period,” Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that the dinosaur skin probably had a reddish-brown coloration.
Researchers are continuing to study the animal and are looking for more information about its life, including the preserved contents of the stomach, to find its last meal.
It is believed that the dinosaur fell into the river after his death and was taken to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
In the Alberta area, the climate was the same as in present-day Florida, and the rivers and oceans were much further inland than they are today.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it’s completely covered in perfectly preserved skin and at the same time preserved in three dimensions so we can see its original size,” Brown said.
‘For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as at the time of the chalk.
You don’t have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; you just have to close your eyes a little and it seems like you’re just sleeping.’
During the Cretaceous period, huge theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, walked around the Earth on two legs.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - Tyrannosaurus rex - lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been a favorite prey of his equally terrifying ancestors.
They include Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5-meter-long monster with a weight of over 6 tons.
