How did one activist learn the answer to the question: ‘Whose Streets?’
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook her entire body.
The day after she arrived in New York, a native of St. Louis sat on the bed in an Airbnb room and browsed Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across a contribution from a high school student.
"Police just shot an 18-year-old boy whose body is still on the street," he said.
She was surprised that no one else had written her this post, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A @TheePharoah user retweeted her wall posts all the time.
The St. Louis rapper tweeted about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old man shot by a white-skinned police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying unruly on the street, from where no one had taken him after four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought.
Death was nothing new to her and her family.
She put down her phone to come back to him the night she watched tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
One of the men claimed to be the father of the victim, holding a sign that read, "Ferguson police killed my unarmed son"!
She watched the live news - one of the police officers stood in front of a group of protesters, holding a lead and his barking dog at the other end.
In another video, another police officer, she said, was holding a gun with which he aimed at the crowd and shouted, "I'm going to kill you all... animals."
"It's not normal," Ferrell said.
“This is not the type of murder we’re used to and we can call normal.
I felt goosebumps all over my body.
"I was angry and I cried."
She immediately booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 23:00, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided to go to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years describes a new documentary "Whose Streets?", which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and resistance, strength and inviolability told from the point of view of people living in the community, who take to the streets and demand answers.
On her way to Ferguson, Ferrell engaged in a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral suit and the same floral forehead - on a subject that had been discussed many times before - "about the experience with black people."
“Do you remember how I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?” she recalls.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old, and that's not right."
"It didn't come into my mind that I wouldn't take her with me," Ferrell later said.
“Today’s events are the culmination... of what happened in the past.
She had to know it and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but she also needed to know the difference between the different layers of experience with black people and what we need to do to free ourselves.
Even though I am able to provide her with conditions in which she does not experience racism on her own, she is in no way different from any other black child-woman.
I feel that if I protected her from this experience, I would only harm her.”
After arriving in Ferguson, the first stop on the South Florissant Road was opposite the police department, which became the base of the activists, who were waiting for the words of policeman Darren Wilson about his possible participation in the incident.
Here, Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who was preparing food for others.
Together they prepared the food in bags and helped spread it to the Protestants.
In Ferrell’s eyes, a new type of activism was slowly being born.
"My activism turned upside down after August 9th," Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association Assn. and sought to introduce health care and food to black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural.”
A few weeks later, during the evening demonstration, Ferrell met with the document’s later co-director, Sabaah Folayan.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "just document" the ongoing events.
Ferrell thought, “Are you working on a document or are you trying to find a story that could be used?”
This type of skepticism penetrated into the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to make money from pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We’ve heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are very often forgotten, and we wanted to change that.”
Folayan has already collaborated with co-director Damon Davis, who is a recognized local artist who deals with the subject of prisoners in the cell of death.
His participation in the project also intrigued Ferrell and, along with six other locals, who followed the "Whose Streets?" team in the years following Brown's murder.
"No one speaks for us in this document, but it's our statement," Davis said.
“That was important to me – how these people will be represented – because in the same way I will be represented.”
While the goal of the document was not to focus on Ferrell’s experiences — in an effort to show that the movement “is not about a savior leader, but about bringing the community closer together,” Folayan said — it turned out to be she who is most open to participating in filming.
"Whose Streets?" describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, such as how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face, thinking of the first moment she looked at the final version of the document.
"But I understood that in order to do this job and polish the blacks, I have to open up."
Ferrell’s story also emphasizes the role of the extreme black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement’s three founders – who created a social media campaign under #BlackLivesMatter in 2012 in response to the murder of teenager Trayvon Martin – call themselves freaks.
“Black women in extreme positions are ultimately behind the preservation of the movement,” Ferrell said, “because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black, eccentric women must bear the brunt of these events.”
Folayan agrees with this statement, adding that "the movement is in fact supported by black women and a large number of disgruntled black women."
She insists, however, that "this is not just an affirmative matter" and that Ferrell is not the main hero of the document because of her views.
"It was she who was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
"That she was in the front lines is no accident, because life at these crossroads in the skin of a black strange woman is dangerous.
You can feel the energy in front of the screen.”
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, TV station cameras have cleared their positions, but heavy racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is on a two-and-a-half-year probation to block the highway during the demonstrations.
The social-political atmosphere in the area she calls home has been described as "disorder."
Yet she does not stop in her pursuit, which she has been committed to ever since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
The only thing we can lose is our chains.”
