A Becoming Resemblance: Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery is placed several faces of different skin shades - white, black and brown - hanging from the ceiling on the wires. Each of them as if from the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from mouthwashes and hairs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning has sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized publication of secret cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, informatics and art, and Manning, a transsexual and pioneering dissident whose sentence was reduced by Obama three days before he left office.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and the use of 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a shrewd, if not intellectual, commentary on the subjectivity of DNA - as well as on the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the indescribable nature of DNA.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has been talking about being considered a woman since she was young. She was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including breaking six espionage laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photographs were taken by prison staff, and only one black-and-white, lower-quality photograph was leaked to the public, in which Manning, visibly concerned, sits in the driver's seat in a platinum blonde wig with which she is now associated.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the Dewey-Hagborg project from 2012 Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic items - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create a picture of possible forms of these people.
And it was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning in prison and they wanted to add a portrait to the article,” Dewey-Hagborg said at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, they were not allowed to visit or take photographs, so they asked Chelsea if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse were reunited over a period of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the exhibitions in person.
President Obama did indeed request Manning’s release a few days after the comic was released, a welcome change after several unbearable years spent in a military prison in Kansas.
It’s really interesting that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging war with people who seek to publicize government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to instigate resentment in the areas he should be promoting with his tweets.
In response to a question about this special timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that “everything happens for a reason.”
Under the statement of the artist on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter "i" in the surname is pierced with the heart) after the end of "self-acting factionalism, which is based on gender, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite side are the sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a hundredth of the letters C, G and A recorded by the pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the sophisticated scientific dictionary of the artist), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
“I hope people will take it from us that our genome doesn’t matter who we are and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it their own way,” Dewey-Hagborg said.
"DNA tells a lot of different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last copy of the exhibition, placed in a separate room, is the only page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging in the King Kong manner from the United States Disciplinary Barracks prison with a megaphone in his hand.
"As soon as they prevent you from speaking, they will win," she wrote.
“Never let yourself be silenced.”
"It's a direct transcript of one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goosebumps."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibition – which was predicted in the comics – but when it does, she will be welcomed in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genomic likenesses, arranged as a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded with a pencil.
"In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel like a crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates it.”
