Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but did not find a suitable survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even misleading.
And even though she promised anonymity to the survey, some employees expressed their distrust throughout the process.
"I was looking for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, an e-commerce owner of San Francisco-based hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
She asked for help from the outside.
New human resources startups are constantly appearing on the market, helping companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intent of measuring employee responsibilities, startups enable companies to make quick voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer full employee anonymity and a hotline for filing complaints, and in some cases also inform the public about them.
“There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that thanks to Glint, she gained more awareness in three years about what her employees think and feel.
In addition to quick surveys and voting by specific teams, Glint offers a temperature map of the company and a casual overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of managers with low ratings - allowing the user to work on the correction.
Companies are starting to realize that it is necessary to pay attention to the culture of the work environment - in case another Uber becomes one of them - which is thrown off in scandals after a former employee posted on his blog a post describing the corporate environment and harassing employees who give up.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let's Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
The Denver, Colorado-based startup Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the start of the year, just ahead of Uber’s scandals.
Nearly 600 of Convercent’s clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has also recently taken the plunge.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customisable “flash” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints are sent directly to the Management Board.
“The court of public opinion has regulators in place,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of the startup Convercent.
If the company is convicted of mishandling its employees or unethical behavior — and if regulators fail to act — it may face costly consequences as a result of a customer boycott, employee exhaustion, or court proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employees’ awareness of corporate policies and procedures and to ensure an easy way to contact corporate management.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problems, he had to search the phone number or email to the company management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
