The Making of a Graphic Novel: The Story of A Castle in England
Scotney Castle played the lead role in Squeeze's music video, and Margaret Thatcher took refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
However, Scotney witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his cozy spot on the Bewl River in Kent, England, which inspired the quirky Jamie Rhodes of York County – known for his love of historical documents – to create a graphic novel.
“Looking at a man’s handwriting 300 years after his death fascinates me,” says Rhodes with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived at Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story illustrates a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, it is not the first Rhodes book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by the British Library's documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the fingerprints on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And the letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm back in time.
I love the archives!”
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to spend almost four months at the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, browsing through the archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on a wall and bottles that had been thrown away for centuries in a moat.
He walked around the grounds and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking to the hajni, gardeners and sometimes also to artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
At night, he "drinked whiskey and wrote."
The confidential history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust gained access to the documents only in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived at the site ten years later, employees were only beginning to penetrate the archives that Rhodes described in words, as if “aristocrats of many centuries are throwing up their hands with the words: ‘Put it in the attic’.”
Newspapers, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps depicting property: “You may think the land dispute is boring,” Rhodes said, “but I came across one case where two families were dragging along the birch tree.
Stop it, people!"
Some stories in the book use the castle as a reflection bridge and dig deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves a newly built castle to join the English Uprising of 1381.
“I found a record of the revolt at the castle in 1380, which was called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,” Rhodes said.
“The English rebellion actually started in this area and I thought the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe it’s somehow related.”
Other stories are firmly linked to the castle's history - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest who was hidden by the Darrell family for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled a casket with stones (which was discovered only a few years after the casket was discovered).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was intrigued by the male generation - the men of that time were always in debt and spent money on things they couldn't afford.
The different generations of the Darrell family solved this by taking rich or old ladies - I imagine it was the handsome gentlemen who were fond of biting the heads of the heirs."
With the end of his stay at the castle, he searches for Rhodes after other adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book on El<0xC3><0xA4>m<0xC3><0xA4>nm<0xC3><0xA4>ki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was engulfed in nature.
This is a very special place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
“I thought, ‘Now I’m going to go back to real life.’”
