Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD).
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
However, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that support the resistance of the intestines, which is why it has been shown to reduce the risk of developing cancer.
The study’s lead author, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that support tolerance and protect the body without damaging the sensitive tissue.
As soon as the scales are tilted to the side of the inflammation, an inflammatory disease of the intestine can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells that promote body tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins to create cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We found a link between one type of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support body tolerance.
The more tryptophan mice had in their diet, the more they had these immune cells.”
At the same time, he suggested that if it turns out that the same applies to humans, then a combination of L. reuteri bacteria and a diet rich in tryptophan would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory intestinal environment.
Postgraduate researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in a study of a certain type of immune cell supporting body tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice kept separately cells were missing.
She deduced that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome — a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that commonly reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The intestines of mice were tested by DNA sorting, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
The mice, which were bred in a sterile environment and lacked a gut microbiome - so they did not develop this type of immune cell - were given the L. reuteri bacteria - and formed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in the fluid and then transferred small amounts of fluid—without the bacteria—to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it was shown to be a by-product of a tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-octave acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. After splitting the doses of tryptophan, at the same time, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice and most of us store L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the by-products of tryptophan from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
"Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri bacteria may increase the cell population."
