White House props cost thousands of dollars to taxpayers
The White House’s decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry, which took place last month, came at $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17th program at the White House, which was a showcase of U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials watched the show of products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was on display alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" incident, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) records said.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such a significant event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an e-mail to his superior, a representative of the Navy's Air Force commander, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter will arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 a.m. for the occasion of the show, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and will remain in place until the entire site is completely cleared, which was scheduled between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail further stated that in the event of a delay on departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for return flights due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained on the scene that evening along with the helicopter and with them also a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by the weekly TIME - it was not clear whether the second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prohibits government officials from using government assets for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible violation of this regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were sure that everything was fine," the commander wrote.
"It sounds like they're blocking you," the deputy commander wrote.
The "Made in America" show was designated by the White House as an official event and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
During his participation in the event, the president advocated health reform, which was passed by the Senate, and talked about trying to keep the government regulations in check.
The use of air transport, such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes, is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for the sake of presentation is unusual.
Trump ordered a check in February after the presidential plane was in the background at his first meeting as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is plagued by complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
“The White House is delighted with the ‘Made in America’ show, which showcased products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials,” said press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington area and on the South Lawn, rehearsing possible flights with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the crew’s current training, the state official said.
On the same day, the helicopter’s unit was on “non-presidential support missions” for another eleven hours.
The White House said no additional props were paid out of taxpayers' money.
Spokesman Sikorsky said the company was not in any way interested in the negotiations for the South Lawn helicopter exhibition.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights and the exact costs associated with the parade are difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Department of Defense, the hourly price for fiscal year 2017 is $24,380 per flight hour, replacing DoD expenses for VH-3D.
The unit's records show a time of 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of helicopters are well below that amount.
"Indicate the costs of taxpayers based on estimates for reimbursement of expenses is very misleading," Walters said of the case.
“These estimates include staff, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual costs.”
According to the 2015 RAND study, reimbursements for DoD expenses do not include staff costs, but include fuel price, maintenance and contract costs.
The then White House press secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the purpose of the show.
“The idea of this week’s show is to introduce products made in the U.S.,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state and provide jobs to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens are involved in producing.
This fact should be remembered.”
It is not clear whether Trump was also seen on a helicopter during his tour of the South Lawn. With certainty, it can only be said that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House, Trump addressed a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three of them myself."
