According to the UN, Afghan democracy relies on women in politics.
Elections can only be credible if they are attended by all members of the society, including women, the UN representative in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, the head of the United Nations Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA), said hundreds of women are taking part in local elections, three women are running for vice president, and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
"The role of women cannot be overlooked," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can be fully representative and credible only if women are also involved, as well as all related processes related to the elections.
The presidential and local elections in Afghanistan will be held on April 5.
The Taliban has issued several threats against the electoral process, which shifts international combat activity to the second round.
In this year’s elections, for the first time ever, a democratically elected government transfers its power peacefully to the next government.
Haysom said that the strong role of women will strengthen Afghanistan’s democracy.
The Afghan Independent Electoral Commission said that of the 3.6 million registered voters, 1.2 million are women.
