GMB chief organizer Drew Duffy added: “The fact that we have not received a clear response from the builder regarding the company’s needs and the future investment plan at Tollcross is very worrying for our members.
Generations of many families have worked here, and the employees come mostly from the local community and the Glasgow area, where working in the local factory represents a critical pillar of decent employment in the area of high unemployment and social exclusion.
In terms of jobs, wages and benefits – and despite the prospect of Brexit, rising living costs and declining slow production – the eastern part of Glasgow needs a desperately prosperous producer like McVitie’s.”
A spokesperson for Pladis said: “Constructor Tollcross received a letter from GMB only yesterday and the company will issue a statement as soon as possible as we appreciate the continued commitment to employees and union representatives.
A regular meeting with GMB employees and representatives in Tollcross took place two months ago and many issues were openly discussed at this meeting.
We talked to employees that, as in all companies operating in extremely competitive and uncertain economic conditions, we evaluate our operations on a regular basis, which applies to all our operations so that we can continue to successfully compete with others.
She added: “In recent years, we have invested <0xC2><0xA3>5 million in Tollcross, particularly in production lines and streamlining operations.
We greatly appreciate the heritage of Tollcross and the local location and in case of any changes in the operation of the local factory, the employees and representatives of the trade unions will be informed immediately."
